\begin_layout Standard
Of the three situations given in the question, case 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the only one where the real moral hazard problem arises.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First consider case 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Here Low effort gives the principal an expected payoff of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1\ast10+0.9\ast100=91$
\end_inset

, whereas High effort gives 
\begin_inset Formula $0.9\ast10+0.1\ast100=19$
\end_inset

.
 The principal would prefer the agent to give Low effort.
 The agent on his part always prefers to give low effort, because it involves
 low disutility.
 So in this case there is no moral hazard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Next, consider case 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Here, High effort gives 100 for sure.
 So if the principal ever observes an outcome of 10, he will conclude that
 the agent must have given Low effort.
 This helps the principal write a contract in which an outcome of 10 is
 always punishable.
 The punishment can be made appropriately large so that the agent will be
 deterred from giving low effort.
 So here though the moral hazard problem potentially exists, it can be solved
 easily as effort is in effect observable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now consider case 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Here Low effort gives a lower expected payoff (
\begin_inset Formula $37$
\end_inset

), and High effort gives a higher expected payoff (
\begin_inset Formula $91$
\end_inset

).
 The principal prefers High effort, but the agent prefers Low effort, and
 the principal cannot determine the agent's effort from the outcome observed.
 Hence, there is a moral hazard problem.
