\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) The agent that does not exert effort will have expected payoff:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
EU_{e=0}=p_{0}u(Q+\overline{w})+(1-p_{0})u(\underline{w})
\]

\end_inset

 The agent that exerts effort will have expected payoff:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
EU_{e=1}=p_{1}u(Q+\overline{w})+(1-p_{1})u(\underline{w})-C
\]

\end_inset

Since effort is monitorable, the agent's incentive compatibility constraint
 (
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1}-p_{0})(u(Q+\overline{w})-u(\underline{w}))\geq C$
\end_inset

) does not come into account, and one only has to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $EU_{e=1}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) The employer will maximize its objective function 
\begin_inset Formula $EU_{e=1}$
\end_inset

 (the utility of the agent) s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\overline{w}+(1-p_{1})\underline{w}\geq0$
\end_inset

 (this is the budget constraint for the employer)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \max p_{1}u(Q+\overline{w})+(1-p_{1})u(\underline{w})-C\\
\text{s.t. }p_{1}\overline{w}+(1-p_{1})\underline{w} & \geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) The budget constraint will be binding, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\overline{w}+(1-p_{1})\underline{w}=0$
\end_inset

 and the government maximizes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\overline{t}}{\max}p_{1}u(Q+\overline{w})+(1-p_{1})u(\frac{-p_{1}\overline{w}}{1-p_{1}})-C
\]

\end_inset

 so that at the optimum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w}) & =u^{\prime}(\frac{-p_{1}\overline{w}}{1-p_{1}})\\
 & \text{so}\\
u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w}) & =u^{\prime}(\underline{w})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so s.t.
 monotonicity conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q+\overline{w}=\underline{w}$
\end_inset

 (this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{w}<0$
\end_inset

).
 This is explained by the wish of the government to minimize the variability
 of the income of the agent as the agent is risk averse.
 Note that if effort wasn't verifiable, then the agent would not do effort
 as income is the same either way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) If effort is not verifiable, then the agent must be induced to choose
 to do effort, so the program of the principal is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \max p_{1}u(Q+\overline{w})+(1-p_{1})u(\underline{w})-C\\
\text{s.t. }p_{1}\overline{w}+(1-p_{1})\underline{w} & \geq0\text{ (budget constraint)}\\
(p_{1}-p_{0})(u(Q+\overline{w})-u(\underline{w})) & \geq C\text{ (incentive constraint)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) The Lagrangian of the optimization problem is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=p_{1}u(\overline{w})+(1-p_{1})u(\underline{w})-C-\mu(p_{1}\overline{w}+(1-p_{1})\underline{w})-\lambda(C_{1}-(p_{1}-p_{0})(u(Q+\overline{w})-u(\underline{w})))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions for maximization are as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{1}u^{\prime}(\overline{w})-\mu p_{1}+\lambda(p_{1}-p_{0})u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w}) & =0\\
(1-p_{1})u^{\prime}(\underline{w})-\mu(1-p_{1})-\lambda(p_{1}-p_{0})u^{\prime}(\underline{w}) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first condition can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{\prime}(\overline{w})+\lambda(1-\frac{p_{0}}{p_{1}})u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w})=\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we can already see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu>0$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is positive (since 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}(\overline{w})\geq0$
\end_inset

 (increasing utility function)).
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing this expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 into the second condition, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1-\lambda\frac{p_{1}-p_{0}}{1-p_{1}})u^{\prime}(\underline{w}) & =u^{\prime}(\overline{w})+\lambda(1-\frac{\pi_{0}}{\pi_{1}})u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w})\\
u^{\prime}(\underline{w})-u^{\prime}(\overline{w}) & =\lambda\lbrack\frac{p_{1}-p_{0}}{1-p_{1}}u^{\prime}(\underline{w})+(1-\frac{\pi_{0}}{\pi_{1}})u^{\prime}(Q+\overline{w})]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}(\underline{w})-u^{\prime}(\overline{w})>0$
\end_inset

 which is the case as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{w}\leq\overline{w}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 will be positive at the optimum so the two constraints, budget and incentive,
 will be binding:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{1}\overline{w}+(1-\pi_{1})\underline{w} & =0\\
C-(p_{1}-p_{0})(u(\overline{w})-u(\underline{w})) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means that in order to induce effort, the government will have to different
iate payment between the high and the low payoff in order to induce the
 agent to seek to increase the probability of the high payoff by exerting
 effort.
 This comes at the expense of making the payoff to the agent more uncertain.
