 is to be paid and worked in case of a favourable shock and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{L}=(w_{L},h_{L})$
\end_inset

 is to be paid and worked in case of an adverse shock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2,$
\end_inset

 the agent accepts or reject the contract.
 If the contract is rejected, the game ends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=3,$
\end_inset

 the outcome is realized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=4,$
\end_inset

 transfers are made according to the contract and the realization of the
 outcome.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
c) The principal's objective function is its expected profit 
\begin_inset Formula $E\pi:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\pi=q(x_{H}h_{H}-w_{H})+(1-q)(x_{L}h_{L}-w_{L})
\]

\end_inset

 The agent's individual rationality constraint is such that its expected
 utility 
\begin_inset Formula $EU$
\end_inset

 is positive:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
d) The Lagrangian of the optimization problem is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=q(x_{H}h_{H}-w_{H})+(1-q)(x_{L}h_{L}-w_{L})+\lambda(q(u(w_{H})-f(h_{H}))+(1-q)(u(w_{L})-f(h_{L})))
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 the Lagrange multiplier for the rationality constraint.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Maximization in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 obtains that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q(u(w_{H})-f(h_{H}))+(1-q)(u(w_{H})-f(h_{H}))=0
\]

\end_inset

 so the rationality constraint is binding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximization in 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{H},h_{L},w_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{L}$
\end_inset

 obtains the following first order conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{H}-\lambda f^{\prime}(h_{H}) & =0\\
x_{L}-\lambda f^{\prime}(h_{L}) & =0\\
-1+\lambda u^{\prime}(w_{H}) & =0\\
-1+\lambda u^{\prime}(w_{L}) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
e) From the above equalities, I obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{x_{H}}{f^{\prime}(h_{H})} & =\lambda\\
\frac{x_{L}}{f^{\prime}(h_{L})} & =\lambda\\
\lambda u^{\prime}(w_{H}) & =1\\
\lambda u^{\prime}(w_{L}) & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}(w_{H})=u^{\prime}(w_{L})$
\end_inset

 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{H}=w_{L}.$
\end_inset

 The agent is paid the same wage irrespective of the shock because the agent
 is risk averse.
 Now, from the two first equalities, I have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{H}}{f^{\prime}(h_{H})}=\frac{x_{L}}{f^{\prime}(h_{L})}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}(h_{L})=\frac{x_{L}}{x_{H}}f^{\prime}(h_{H})
\]

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{L}<x_{H}$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}(h_{L})<f^{\prime}(h_{H})
\]

\end_inset

 so the agent works less in case of a negative shock (this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is increasing as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is convex).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
f) Under the contract above, the principal has to pay the same wage whether
 the agent works 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{H}$
\end_inset

 hours or 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{L}$
\end_inset

 hours.
 This means that in case of a negative shock, the principal will want to
 lie and pretend there was a positive shock so the agent has to work more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
g) One must include incentive constraints for the principal so it does not
 lie, so one needs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{H}h_{H}-w_{H}\geq x_{H}h_{L}-w_{L}
\]

\end_inset

 so the principal pays 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{H}$
\end_inset

 and asks the worker to work 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{H}$
\end_inset

 hours in case of a positive shock, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{L}h_{L}-w_{L}\geq x_{L}h_{H}-w_{H}
\]

\end_inset

 so the principal pays 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{L}$
\end_inset

 and asks the worker to work 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{L}$
\end_inset

 hours in case of a negative shock.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Adding up those two conditions, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{H}h_{H}-w_{H}+x_{L}h_{L}-w_{L} & \geq x_{H}h_{L}-w_{L}+x_{L}h_{H}-w_{H}\\
(x_{H}-x_{L})h_{H} & \geq(x_{H}-x_{L})h_{L}\\
h_{H} & \geq h_{L}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 so the agent will be asked to work more in case of a positive shock.
 Then, looking at the second incentive constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{H}-w_{L}\geq x_{L}(h_{H}-h_{L})
\]

\end_inset

so the agent will be paid more in case of a positive shock than in case
 of a negative shock.
 This means that the first best outcome cannot be achieved if the principal
 can lie.
 The possibility of lying works to the detriment of the principal.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
